", "whylisten": "

Ken Kamler has practiced medicine in some of the most extreme conditions on Earth -- from the Andes mountains to the Antarctic ice to the Amazon rainforest. Many of his expeditions have been in concert with National Geographic, helping teams to carry out geological research and precision mapping less traveled areas of the world. He has also served as the chief high altitude physician in research by NASA, helping examine the human body’s response to high altitudes.

When not on expedition to a remote corner of the globe, Kamler practices microsurgery, specializing in hand reconstruction and finger reattachment. He has also chronicled his adventures in the books Doctor on Everest and Surviving the Extremes: A Doctor's Journey to the Limits of Human Endurance. His treatment of the climbers in the largest disaster to happen on Mount Everest was portrayed in the book Into Thin Air and in the IMAX film documentary, Everest. He has been active in promoting the Boy Scouts of America and currently serves as their Founders District Chairman in Queens, NY.

aws-transcripts.transcript: Okay, well, we've heard a lot of people speak this'll conference about the power of the human mind. And what I'd like to do today is give you a vivid example of how that power could be unleashed when someone is in a survival situation. How the will to survive in bring that out in people. Uh, this is Ah, an incident which occurred on Mount Everest was the worst disaster in the history of Everest on when it occurred, I was the only doctor on the mountain. So I'll take you through that and, uh, we'll see what it's like when someone really summons the will to survive. Okay, This Mount Everest, it's 29,035 feet high. I've been there six times. Four times. I did work with National Geographic making tectonic plate measurements. Twice I went with NASA doing road sensing devices. It was on my fourth trip to Everest that a comet passed over the mountains. Higher crude. Taki and the Sherpas told us then that that was a very bad omen and we should have listened to him. Everest is an extreme environment. There's only 1/3 as much oxygen at the summit is, there is a sea level nearthe summit. Temperatures could be 40 degrees below zero. You can have wins 20 to 40 miles an hour. It's actually a wind chill factor, which is lower than a summer day on Mars. I remember one time being up near the summit, I reached into my down jacket for drink from my water bottle inside my down jacket, only to discover that the water was already frozen solid gives you an idea of just how severe things are any of the summit. Okay, here's the route up Everest. It's starts a base camp, a 17,500 feet camp, 1 2000 feet higher camp to another 2000 feet higher up what's called the Western kun.
